1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,510
I'd like to now walk you through how to gather JSON data using

2
00:00:03,510 --> 00:00:07,425
the request library and access data within JSON files in Python.

3
00:00:07,425 --> 00:00:10,950
We'll be looking at the JSON from the archive.org.item.

4
00:00:10,950 --> 00:00:13,470
First, let's take a look at how we can use

5
00:00:13,470 --> 00:00:17,640
Python's built-in json module to extract JSON data from a request.

6
00:00:17,640 --> 00:00:21,540
We'll start with importing our request in JSON libraries and then making

7
00:00:21,540 --> 00:00:26,710
an HTTP GET Request to the book on archive.org using the requests library.

8
00:00:26,810 --> 00:00:32,400
Perfect. Now we want to access the output of this request which contains the json.

9
00:00:32,400 --> 00:00:35,445
If I use the method book.content,

10
00:00:35,445 --> 00:00:38,115
note how I get a byte string.

11
00:00:38,115 --> 00:00:41,105
If I want the output of the request in Unicode,

12
00:00:41,105 --> 00:00:47,030
I can go ahead and use the.text method so I can see the texts better.

13
00:00:47,030 --> 00:00:51,120
Note how if we use the.text method,

14
00:00:52,580 --> 00:00:55,800
the output is in a string format.

15
00:00:55,800 --> 00:00:58,755
See the apostrophe before the curly braces.

16
00:00:58,755 --> 00:01:03,260
How do we convert this string with a JSON object in it to just a Python object?

17
00:01:03,260 --> 00:01:07,355
Here we're going to go ahead, scroll down and use the json.loads function,

18
00:01:07,355 --> 00:01:10,370
which does just that, to de-serialize the string

19
00:01:10,370 --> 00:01:13,765
that we're getting from the.text method into a Python dictionary.

20
00:01:13,765 --> 00:01:16,620
Here using json.loads on book.text,

21
00:01:16,620 --> 00:01:18,705
we have now a Python dictionary.

22
00:01:18,705 --> 00:01:23,915
We'll take a moment to get back to inspecting the output of this in a bit.

23
00:01:23,915 --> 00:01:25,545
I want to note a quick thing.

24
00:01:25,545 --> 00:01:30,705
You can actually also use json.loads on the outputs of the.content method as well.

25
00:01:30,705 --> 00:01:33,350
This is because you can also use.loads to

26
00:01:33,350 --> 00:01:36,940
de-serialize bytes or byte arrays in addition to strings.

27
00:01:36,940 --> 00:01:38,195
As we can see here,

28
00:01:38,195 --> 00:01:41,950
it works just fine on our byte output as well.

29
00:01:41,950 --> 00:01:46,700
Now, let's take a look at another option that is much more popular and simpler.

30
00:01:46,700 --> 00:01:51,305
Here I'm making my HTTP GET Request again and using the.json

31
00:01:51,305 --> 00:01:56,540
method of a response object from the request library to extract the JSON data.

32
00:01:56,540 --> 00:01:59,240
Now we can see after just using.json,

33
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:01,165
it's ready to use.

34
00:02:01,165 --> 00:02:06,395
Next let's actually inspect this data regarding metadata about the book more closely.

35
00:02:06,395 --> 00:02:10,160
We have a lot of data and nesting that's taking place in this JSON.

36
00:02:10,160 --> 00:02:13,460
Some data includes the number of files associated with the book,

37
00:02:13,460 --> 00:02:15,410
like this thumbnail file.

38
00:02:15,410 --> 00:02:19,400
In addition, we can also scroll down all the way here and

39
00:02:19,400 --> 00:02:23,255
see additional information about the camera that was used for capturing the book,

40
00:02:23,255 --> 00:02:25,625
the publisher, the date, etc.

41
00:02:25,625 --> 00:02:28,435
Let's see now how to access some of this data.

42
00:02:28,435 --> 00:02:32,435
Let's start with accessing one of the first attributes, the directory.

43
00:02:32,435 --> 00:02:35,090
Scrolling up here, we can see that we have that

44
00:02:35,090 --> 00:02:39,430
as one of our first attributes as part of the JSON file.

45
00:02:39,430 --> 00:02:45,065
Note how I use the brackets to do so in order to access the dir key.

46
00:02:45,065 --> 00:02:48,260
Let's actually move on to something a bit more complicated,

47
00:02:48,260 --> 00:02:51,440
now that we can see that we can print the result in value for that key.

48
00:02:51,440 --> 00:02:55,085
I want to show you how we can access the review title.

49
00:02:55,085 --> 00:03:00,055
Here first, I have to access the metadata attribute as part of this huge JSON.

50
00:03:00,055 --> 00:03:02,885
Now note that the metadata attribute is actually

51
00:03:02,885 --> 00:03:06,335
a JSON object containing many key value pairs.

52
00:03:06,335 --> 00:03:08,600
See the title key here, for example,

53
00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:10,735
which is nestled within the metadata attribute.

54
00:03:10,735 --> 00:03:12,885
That's what we need. To access it,

55
00:03:12,885 --> 00:03:15,860
I need to use metadata and then title.

56
00:03:15,860 --> 00:03:17,945
Let's look at what that looks like.

57
00:03:17,945 --> 00:03:22,075
Now I'm able to get the full title of the book pro-grammatically.

58
00:03:22,075 --> 00:03:25,660
Let's take a look at some of the reviews data for the book.

59
00:03:25,660 --> 00:03:31,100
First, let's go ahead and use a similar methodology of accessing the reviews attribute.

60
00:03:31,100 --> 00:03:34,480
Now the reviews key is containing a JSON array,

61
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:36,440
as you can see with the square brackets here,

62
00:03:36,440 --> 00:03:39,755
with exactly one JSON object or element in it.

63
00:03:39,755 --> 00:03:45,545
Let's access the only JSON object in this JSON array using the indexing value of zero.

64
00:03:45,545 --> 00:03:48,860
Notice now how the square brackets are now disappeared from

65
00:03:48,860 --> 00:03:52,415
our output since this is the only element in the list.

66
00:03:52,415 --> 00:03:55,565
Now with JSON object reviews zero,

67
00:03:55,565 --> 00:03:58,925
we now have one JSON object with many key value pairs.

68
00:03:58,925 --> 00:04:01,325
Now one of these keys is review body.

69
00:04:01,325 --> 00:04:03,695
Let's go ahead and see if we can access this.

70
00:04:03,695 --> 00:04:06,665
I can access this by doing json_book_text,

71
00:04:06,665 --> 00:04:07,790
indexing by reviews,

72
00:04:07,790 --> 00:04:12,560
zero, and reviewbody to get the content of my review.

73
00:04:12,560 --> 00:04:16,270
Now finally, I want to show you something really complicated.

74
00:04:16,270 --> 00:04:17,735
Check out the files attribute,

75
00:04:17,735 --> 00:04:19,640
which contains information about a number of

76
00:04:19,640 --> 00:04:23,240
different file download options that archive.org provides for the book,

77
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:25,430
including the thumbnail, as we saw earlier,

78
00:04:25,430 --> 00:04:28,175
options to download as a PDF,

79
00:04:28,175 --> 00:04:30,940
and a zip file, etc.

80
00:04:30,940 --> 00:04:35,420
Similarly, the structure of the files attribute in a JSON array is

81
00:04:35,420 --> 00:04:39,800
now having multiple JSON objects in it rather than just one JSON object.

82
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:45,995
Let's task ourselves with finding out the size the Raw Cornell book Zip download option.

83
00:04:45,995 --> 00:04:49,560
Here's where it is in the files attribute.

84
00:04:50,680 --> 00:04:56,840
I want to access the size key to get the size of this particular zip file,

85
00:04:56,840 --> 00:04:58,855
which is all the way over here.

86
00:04:58,855 --> 00:05:03,470
Because this JSON array has multiple JSON objects or elements in it,

87
00:05:03,470 --> 00:05:07,730
I need to actually go ahead and find the index of the element for the zip file first.

88
00:05:07,730 --> 00:05:11,620
Let's go ahead to the top of this JSON and count.

89
00:05:11,620 --> 00:05:15,705
For example, we'd be counting our index 0, 1,

90
00:05:15,705 --> 00:05:20,120
2, 3, 4, 5, and 6.

91
00:05:20,120 --> 00:05:22,640
We can see this is actually the sixth element.

92
00:05:22,640 --> 00:05:25,955
Now that I've done this and I got this specific JSON object

93
00:05:25,955 --> 00:05:29,525
for the Raw Cornell Book Zip using the integer index,

94
00:05:29,525 --> 00:05:33,995
I can now access the size key then in order to get the size of the zip file.

95
00:05:33,995 --> 00:05:36,020
Altogether the command is looking like this,

96
00:05:36,020 --> 00:05:38,780
where we have our json_book_text indexing

97
00:05:38,780 --> 00:05:41,615
by the files attribute and then indexing by the integer six,

98
00:05:41,615 --> 00:05:44,795
giving us the data for the Raw Cornell Book Zip download option.

99
00:05:44,795 --> 00:05:49,735
Then we have to index by the size attribute and then get the actual size of this file.

100
00:05:49,735 --> 00:05:55,300
Finally, let's now compare JSON notation and Python dictionary notation.

101
00:05:55,300 --> 00:05:57,300
Here I've got a dictionary.

102
00:05:57,300 --> 00:06:00,860
Firstly, we see how accessing attributes in JSON and dictionaries,

103
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:02,165
it's actually pretty similar.

104
00:06:02,165 --> 00:06:04,430
Look at how we can access the value hello in

105
00:06:04,430 --> 00:06:06,800
this dictionary using the key in the bracket.

106
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:10,250
However, keys in JSON can only be strings, as you may recall,

107
00:06:10,250 --> 00:06:14,285
whereas Python dictionary keys can be any hashable object, like a number.

108
00:06:14,285 --> 00:06:17,615
How do you convert a Python dictionary to a JSON object?

109
00:06:17,615 --> 00:06:20,660
You can use the json.dumps function,

110
00:06:20,660 --> 00:06:23,510
which takes an object and produces a JSON string,

111
00:06:23,510 --> 00:06:25,855
or in other words, serializes it.

112
00:06:25,855 --> 00:06:29,630
Here, note how we are serializing our dictionary object.

113
00:06:29,630 --> 00:06:35,670
Note that this is the opposite of what json.loads does with de-serializing.

